{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608457"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:31:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:31:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15999"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15999"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8690"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63462"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8690"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15999"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48915"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8605"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20795"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20797"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63462"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryological development, the ectoderm differentiates into distinct tissue types. The surface ectoderm is one of these important derivatives that forms several structures in the developing embryo.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the derivatives of surface ectoderm?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Develops into epidermis and its appendages","Produces the neural crest cells","Forms melanocytes and peripheral nerves","Gives rise to the central nervous system","Develops into sensory placodes only"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esurface ectoderm develops into epidermis and its appendages\u003C/strong\u003E, including the skin, hair follicles, nails, sweat glands, and mammary glands. This is distinct from other ectodermal derivatives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMelanocytes and peripheral nerves\u003C/strong\u003E are derived from neural crest cells, not surface ectoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentral nervous system\u003C/strong\u003E develops from neuroectoderm, not surface ectoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeural crest cells\u003C/strong\u003E arise from the neural plate border, between neural and surface ectoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESensory placodes\u003C/strong\u003E are specialised regions of ectoderm that form sense organs, but they are not the only derivatives of surface ectoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the derivatives of surface ectoderm is crucial for comprehending the development of skin and its associated structures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Surface ectoderm gives rise to epidermis, hair follicles, sweat glands, and mammary glands during embryological development.","Surface ectoderm is distinct from neuroectoderm which forms the nervous system."],"references":["Nakanoh S, Sham K, Ghimire S, Mohorianu I, Rayon T, Vallier L. Human surface ectoderm and amniotic ectoderm are sequentially specified according to cellular density. Sci Adv. 2024 Mar;10(9):eadh7748. doi: 10.1126/sciadv.adh7748. Epub 2024 Mar 1. PMID: 38427729; PMCID: PMC10906920.","Gaillard R, Steegers EA, de Jongste JC, Hofman A, Jaddoe VW. Tracking of fetal growth characteristics during different trimesters and the risks of adverse birth outcomes. Int J Epidemiol. 2014 Aug;43(4):1140-53. doi: 10.1093/ije/dyu036. Epub 2014 Mar 5. PMID: 24603318; PMCID: PMC4258770","Chen X, Liu H, Li Y, Zhang W, Zhou A, Xia W, Xu S. First-trimester fetal size, accelerated growth in utero, and child neurodevelopment in a cohort study. BMC Med. 2024 Apr 29;22(1):181. doi: 10.1186/s12916-024-03390-3. PMID: 38685041; PMCID: PMC11059611","Godfrey KM, Inskip HM, Hanson MA. The long-term effects of prenatal development on growth and metabolism. Semin Reprod Med. 2011 May;29(3):257-65. doi: 10.1055/s-0031-1275518. Epub 2011 Jul 18. PMID: 21769765; PMCID: PMC3685133","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48915"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15999"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48915"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T23:05:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T23:06:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8690"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63462"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":